URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS152331833	2018-08-04 09:07:51	26975	species	Crissal Thrasher	Toxostoma crissale			2				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Clark	US-NV-003		33			Overton WMA	L474583	H	36.5134605	-114.4218698	2012-05-11	06:00:00	obsr164698	S10715848	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	210	5.633		1	1		0	1	0				
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154299277	2017-05-15 17:30:19	26975	species	Crissal Thrasher	Toxostoma crissale			1				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Clark	US-NV-003		33	USFWS_591		Desert NWR--Corn Creek (Field Station)	L168656	H	36.4387970	-115.3595660	2012-05-05	05:30:00	obsr235247	S10838974	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	420	3.219		2	1		0	1	0		Experienced an absolutely amazing migrant fallout on 5/5 at Corn Creek just north of Las Vegas.  David Donsker and I arrived at Corn Creek at first light and immediately noticed a number of kingbirds flying into the trees from the desert.  As the steady stream of birds continued, we noticed numerous warblers flying in along with the kingbirds.  The first tree we reached was loaded with Western Kingbirds, although only 10 feet tall it had at least 50 kingbirds on it perched like Christmas tree ornaments.  Each binocular field in each mulberry tree contained at least 5 Bullock's Orioles and a few more Western Kingbirds.  Groups of 5 to 10 warblers (mostly Audubon's) were in the trees, on the ground, in the grass, on fence posts - just everywhere.  We birded the oasis from 5:15 to 11 and conservatively estimated 2,000 birds of 75 species.  Counting was next to impossible as the birds were constantly flitting from tree to tree.  We returned and birded the area again from 2:30 to 5:30, and although activity was much lower, there were still hundreds of migrants, several more still flying in from the desert, and we found several species we didn't have in the morning.   Also saw 1 hybrid Eur Collared-Dove X Mourning Dove but could not determine how to enter this into e-bird.

The reported site is up the canyon from Harriet Lake where several large pipes cross underneath the road.  Lot of potential habitat for it to be in if it is still here.   Weather was interesting with cloudy / semi-foggy conditions at the beginning and eventually clearing to partly cloudy.  Temps approx high 50's to mid+ 60's with slight to modest breeze.   More species than I expected but had to work the area pretty hard to find what I did.  Also saw what was probably a Greater Spreadwing Damselfly at the vireo site for those who follow Odes.  Lastly, lots of Monarch Butterflies as it warmed up, perhaps as many as 10.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS478178602	2018-08-04 09:49:32	26975	species	Crissal Thrasher	Toxostoma crissale			2				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Clark	US-NV-003		33			Henderson Bird Viewing Preserve	L209342	H	36.0749791	-115.0021416	2017-03-24	07:30:00	obsr644318	S35395599	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	150	3.219		1	1		0	1	0				
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS478703110	2020-06-18 10:57:55	26975	species	Crissal Thrasher	Toxostoma crissale			1				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Clark	US-NV-003		33			Las Vegas--Sunset Park	L456488	H	36.0685619	-115.1126862	2017-03-24	12:15:00	obsr113012	S35432912	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	135	1.609		1	1		1	1	0		Beautiful day to be out, warm sun and nice breeze. Wildlife included many prairie dogs, 2 Cottontails and 2 Jackrabbits. Highlight was the water rescue of a Crissal's Thrasher (story on list)	This bird comes with a story. I was only going to walk the trails and avoid the lake area, but after walking the trails I decided to add to my list by going to the lake. I walked up and sat on the east side of the lake on a rock about mid-lake so that I could count waterfowl and Cormorants. While looking towards the island I saw a large-ish bird over the water and it went in, then it came out and hovered over the water before going in again. Not knowing what it was and wanting to find out, I hurried north towards it. I got my bins on it - by now it was swimming. At first I thought it was a female grackle, but as I got closer I saw the curved bill through my bins. There was a fisherman nearby and I asked him to grab his rod and come help me rescue the bird. The Thrasher managed to make it to the lake's retaining wall, but the wall was not climbable for him. He just floated near it. The nice fisherman put his rod under the bird (I forgot to take pictures of this part!) and the bird grabbed hold and he was gently lifted out to safety. I was going to try to pick him up and check for injuries, but he scooted away from me and huddled by a rock. So I sat just out of his view on the rock while he shivered and dried off in the sun. Occasionally I would take a peek at him and he always just looked up at me with his yellow eye. I didn't want to stress him any more than necessary so I mostly just sat there for about 20 minutes and he never moved. I decided to go to my car to get a towel to pick him up and return him to the sagebrush where he would be more comfortable and safer. Because of the distance it would take about 10 minutes so I asked the nice fisherman to keep and eye out so that no person or dog bothered the bird. When I got back, the fisherman told me that he looked and the bird was just gone, but no person or dog had been there. As we talked and looked around the rock the fisherman saw a bird running under the pine trees across the grass and towards the sagebrush. It was the Thrasher! I thought I would try to follow him, but he was quite distant and then he picked up speed and ran/flapped/ran until he disappeared in to the sagebrush. So the story had a happy ending. And the fisherman? Well, God blessed him for his efforts - he caught a 10" Rainbow which was his goal, but he didn't think it would happen.

Bright and sunny. Initially calm but wind becoming a Beaufort four or 5 by 11 a.m. Ran into Martin Meyers, Rose Strickland and Dennis, Daniel from Bulgaria, Scott, and Carl Lundblad.	Heard a thrasher singing then calling in thick Mesquite. Could see its silhouette  jumping around inside but very poor views. Dark gray with a long d-curved bill. It sang continuously and sweetly with a variable warble for quite a while. Then chucked. Never did get good looks. According to Rose Strickland, Dennis, and Martin Meyers, the only expected thrasher here is Crissal.

Looking for sparrows in the sage (Brewer's, Sagebrush, Black-throated, etc.) and waterbirds on the lake.	While about halfway between parking area and southeast lake shore, I was startled when 2 large dark thrashers flew up from the tall sage about 10 meters to my left and dropped back in another 50 meters in front of me. Having just seen several Crissal Thrashers in the last few days in SE Arizona, I was pretty sure of the species. While lamenting that I might not find them again, another flew up slightly closer and perched on a sage and gave a great view for about 90 seconds at eye-level. Large chocolate brown thrasher, long tail, long moderately de-curved bill, long tail, diagnostic rusty/ rufous under-tail coverts, dark eye, whitish chin, black line from base of bill down along throat. I am confident of the species and rejected Sage, Brown, Curve-billed, and Le Conte's, None of the birds vocalized.
